An Animator’s Perspective on Vertebrate Evolution -- t18 Developmental Mechanisms of Morphological Transitions: Examples from Archosaurian Evolution -- t19 Microevolution and the Genetic Basis of Vertebrate Diversity: Examples from Teleost Fishes -- t20 The Age of Transformation: The Triassic Period and the Rise of Today’s Land Vertebrate Fauna -- t21 How Do Homoplasies Arise? Origin and Maintenance of Reproductive Modes in Amphibians -- t22 Rampant Homoplasy in Complex Characters: Repetitive Convergent Evolution of Amphibian Feeding Structures -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow did flying birds evolve from running dinosaurs, terrestrial trotting tetrapods evolve from swimming fish, and whales return to swim in the sea? These are some of the great transformations in the 500-million-year history of vertebrate life. And with the aid of new techniques and approaches across a range of fields—work spanning multiple levels of biological organization from DNA sequences to organs and the physiology and ecology of whole organisms—we are now beginning to unravel the confounding evolutionary mysteries contained in the structure, genes, and fossil record of every living species. This book gathers a diverse team of renowned scientists to capture the excitement of these new discoveries in a collection that is both accessible to students and an important contribution to the future of its field. Marshaling a range of disciplines—from paleobiology to phylogenetics, developmental biology, ecology, and evolutionary biology—the contributors attack particular transformations in the head and neck, trunk, appendages such as fins and limbs, and the whole body, as well as offer synthetic perspectives. Illustrated throughout, Great Transformations in Vertebrate Evolution not only reveals the true origins of whales with legs, fish with elbows, wrists, and necks, and feathered dinosaurs, but also the relevance to our lives today of these extraordinary narratives of change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aVertebratesxEvolution. 0aVertebratesxPhylogeny. 0aVertebrates, Fossil. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAbzhanov, Arhat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaier, David B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiewener, Andrew A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackburn, David C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrainerd, Elizabeth L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrainerd, Elizabeth L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurke, Ann Campbell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClaessens, Leon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrompton, A. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaeschler, Edward B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDial, Kenneth P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDial, Kenneth P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDial, Terry R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleagle, John G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGatesy, Stephen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGingerich, Philip D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeers, Ashley M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHopson, James A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenkins, Farish A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo